# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: animal
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:animal/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The **10th edition of *Systema Naturae*** (Latin; the English title is *A General System of Nature*) is a book written by Swedish naturalist Carl Linnaeus and published in two volumes in 1758 and 1759, which marks the starting point of zoological nomenclature.
[src:animal/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] In it, Linnaeus introduced binomial nomenclature for animals, something he had already done for plants in his 1753 publication of *Species Plantarum*.
[src:animal/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Before 1758, most biological catalogues had used polynomial names for the taxa included, including earlier editions of *Systema Naturae*.
[src:animal/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The first work to consistently apply binomial nomenclature across the animal kingdom was the 10th edition of *Systema Naturae*.
[src:animal/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature therefore chose 1 January 1758 as the "starting point" for zoological nomenclature and asserted that the 10th edition of *Systema Naturae* was to be treated as if published on that date.
[src:animal/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Names published before that date are unavailable, even if they would otherwise satisfy the rules.
[src:animal/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The only work which takes priority over the 10th edition is Carl Alexander Clerck's **Svenska Spindlar** or **Aranei Suecici**, which was published in 1757, but is also to be treated as if published on January 1, 1758.
[src:animal/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] During Linnaeus' lifetime, *Systema Naturae* was under continuous revision.
[src:animal/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Progress was incorporated into new and ever-expanding editions; for example, in his 1st edition (1735), whales and manatees were originally classified as species of fish (as was thought to be the case then).
[src:animal/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] In the 10th edition, they were both moved into the mammal class.
[src:animal/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The animal kingdom, as described by Linnaeus: "Animals enjoy sensation by means of a living organization, animated by a medullary substance; perception by nerves; and motion by the exertion of the will.
[src:animal/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] They have members for the different purposes of life; organs for their different senses; and faculties (or powers) for the application of their different perceptions.
[src:animal/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The list has been broken down into the original six classes Linnaeus described for animals: **Mammalia**, **Aves**, **Amphibia**, **Pisces**, **Insecta**, and **Vermes**.
[src:animal/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] By current standards Pisces and Vermes are informal groupings, Insecta also contained arachnids and crustaceans, and one order of Amphibia comprised sharks, lampreys, and sturgeons.
[src:animal/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Linnaeus described mammals as: "Animals that suckle their young by means of lactiferous teats.
[src:animal/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] In external and internal structure they resemble man: most of them are quadrupeds; and with man, their natural enemy, inhabit the surface of the Earth.
[src:animal/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Linnaeus described birds as: "A beautiful and cheerful portion of created nature consisting of animals having a body covered with feathers and down; protracted and naked jaws (the beak), two wings formed for flight, and two feet.
[src:animal/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Linnaeus described fish as: "Always inhabiting the waters; are swift in their motion and voracious in their appetites.
[src:animal/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] They breathe by means of gills, which are generally united by a bony arch; swim by means of radiate fins, and are mostly covered over with cartilaginous scales.
[src:animal/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Linnaeus described his "Vermes" as: "Animals of slow motion, soft substance, able to increase their bulk and restore parts which have been destroyed, extremely tenacious of life, and the inhabitants of moist places.
[src:animal/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] Many of them are without a distinct head, and most of them without feet.
[src:animal/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] They are principally distinguished by their tentacles (or feelers).
[src:animal/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The second volume, published in 1759, detailed the kingdom Plantae, in which Linnaeus included true plants, as well as fungi, algae and lichens.
[src:animal/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] In addition to repeating the species he had previously listed in his *Species Plantarum* (1753), and those published in the intervening period, Linnaeus described several hundred new plant species.
[src:animal/10th-edition-of-systema-naturae] The species from *Species Plantarum* were numbered sequentially, while the new species were labelled with letters.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] 24-isopropyl cholestane (figure 1, left) is a C30 sterane with chemical formula C30H54 and molecular mass 414.76 g/mol.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] The molecule has a cholestane skeleton with an isopropyl moiety at C24 and is the geologically stable form of 24-isopropyl cholesterol.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] A related and important molecule is 24-n-propyl cholestane (figure 1, right), also with the cholestane skeleton, but with an n-propyl moiety at C24.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] 24-isopropyl cholestane is produced copiously by a particular group of sponges in the class Demospongiae within the phylum Porifera.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] Like other molecular fossils, the presence of 24-isopropyl cholestane in rocks may indicate whether demosponge were living in or near the rock's depositional environment.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] High abundances of 24-isopropyl cholestane are identified in the Precambrian rocks from the Hufq supergroup in Oman, suggesting the presence of sponges prior to the Cambrian explosion.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] However, sponges are not the only organisms that produce 24-isopropyl cholestane, so the identification of this biomarker is not uniquely linked to the presence of demosponge.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] While marine pelagophyte algae predominantly produce 24-n-propylcholestane, they also produce 24-isopropyl cholestane.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] The two possible sources of 24-isopropyl cholestane to rocks, the demosponge and the algae, can be decoupled by considering the ratio of 24-isopropyl cholestane to 24-n-propyl cholestane.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] However, in rocks from Oman, the ratio of steranes is 0.52-16.1, with an average value of 1.51, which strongly suggests input of sponge organic matter.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] Notably, these elevated values disappear during the Cambrian, and the ratio of 24-isopropyl cholestane to 24-n-propyl cholestane is used an age-specific proxy for the Proterozoic-Phanerozoic transition.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] Recent research in molecular clocks has argued that the ability to produce 24-isopropyl cholesterol evolved independently in both the demosponge and algae.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] However, it appears that the biosynthesis evolved earlier in the sponges, during the Neoproterozoic, and that the ability to perform the biosynthesis was not present in algae until the Phanerozoic.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] If correct, these results would give scientists much more confidence in interpreting elevated levels of 24-isopropyl cholestane in ancient rocks as reflecting the presence of sponges.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] Additional evidence for sponge evolution before the Cambrian explosion is found in bioclastic packstones from South Australia.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] Through repeated grinding and photography, researchers constructed 3D models of asymmetric structures with ~1 mm-diameter interconnected channels contained within this rock.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] The complex network of tunnels appears inconsistent with fungi or algae, and the researchers tentatively suggested that they are primitive sponges.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] This interpretation is controversial because the structures pre-date the first appearance of other sponge fossils and the structures are only known to occur within a single sedimentary sequence.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] While Love *et al.* (2009) argues for the presence of sponges in rocks below the Marinoan cap carbonate at ~635 Ma (millions of years ago), Antcliffe (2013) estimates the age of the biomarker-bearing rock to be between 645 Ma and ~580 Ma.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] Most recently, Gold *et al.* (2016) writes that the age of rocks containing 24-isoproylcholestane have an age between ~650 Ma and 540 Ma.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] In all cases, estimates agree that the age of the rocks containing 24-isoproylcholestane pre-date the Cambrian explosion at ~541 Ma.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] The presence of sponges before ~540 Ma has profound implications for the evolution of multicellular life and the coupling of the biosphere to Neoproterozoic climate.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] Climate change before the Cambrian explosion and the subsequent diversification of life are intricately intertwined with understanding the causes of Snowball Earth episodes, the deposition of Banded Iron Formations, and the second step in the rise of atmospheric oxygen.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] In particular, the presence of sponges raises questions of the minimum dissolved O2 content of the oceans in the late Neoproterozoic and the transition from a euxinic Canfield ocean to the modern oxygenated deep-ocean.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] However, sponges appear to require very little O2 to survive, so their presence in the Precambrian may not provide strong constraints on Proterozoic O2 levels.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] 24-isopropyl cholestane can be formed through sedimentary diagenesis of other organic molecules, so the high ratio of 24-isopropyl cholestane to 24-n-propyl cholestane could simply reflect the post-depositional transformation of organic matter.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] Some research has addressed this concern by showing a lack of alteration in other organic molecules, such as hopanes, but subsequent analysis has questioned whether the molecules with minimal alteration could have been contamination from modern petroleum-derived oil.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] There may have been a group of bacteria living symbiotically with the sponges that also produced 24-isopropyl cholestane.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] If these bacteria produced the biomarker throughout geologic time, its presence would not be strictly indicative of demosponge.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] However, as with the marine algae, analysis of the ratio of 24-isopropyl cholestane to 24-n-propyl cholestane may clarify the source of the compounds.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] It is strange to find sponge biomarkers before the Cambrian explosion without accompanying sponge fossils (although there is tentative evidence for sponge-like structures in the latest-Neoproterozoic).
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] Moreover, once fossils of sponges do appear during the Paleozoic, the ratio of 24-isopropyl cholestane to 24-n-propylcholestane returns to its background value.
[src:animal/24-isopropylcholestane] This is surprising because we might expect the ratio to stay elevated or even to increase as metazoa diversified and sponges proliferated.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The study of abiogenesis aims to determine how pre-life chemical reactions gave rise to life under conditions strikingly different from those on Earth today.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] It uses tools from biology and chemistry, attempting a synthesis of many sciences.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Life functions through the chemistry of carbon and water, and builds on four chemical families: lipids for cell membranes, carbohydrates such as sugars, amino acids for protein metabolism, and the nucleic acids DNA and RNA for heredity.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] A theory of abiogenesis must explain the origins and interactions of these classes of molecules.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Many approaches investigate how self-replicating molecules came into existence.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Researchers think that life descends from an RNA world, although other self-replicating and self-catalyzing molecules may have preceded RNA.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Other approaches ("metabolism-first" hypotheses) focus on how catalysis on the early Earth might have provided the precursor molecules for self-replication.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The 1952 Miller–Urey experiment demonstrated that amino acids can be synthesized from inorganic compounds under conditions like early Earth's.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Subsequently, amino acids have been found in meteorites, comets, asteroids, and star-forming regions of space.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] While the last universal common ancestor of all modern organisms (LUCA) existed millions of years after the origin of life, its study can guide research into early universal characteristics.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] A genomics approach has sought to characterize LUCA by identifying the genes shared by Archaea and Bacteria, major branches of life.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] It appears there are 60 proteins common to all life and 355 prokaryotic genes that trace to LUCA; their functions imply that LUCA was anaerobic with the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway, deriving energy by chemiosmosis, and used DNA, the genetic code, and ribosomes.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Earlier cells might have had a leaky membrane and been powered by a naturally occurring proton gradient near a deep-sea white smoker hydrothermal vent; or, life may have originated inside the continental crust or in water at Earth's surface.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth is the only place known to harbor life, astrobiologists assume that life exists and came into being by similar processes on other planets.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Geochemical and fossil evidence informs most studies.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The Earth was formed at 4.54 Gya, and the earliest evidence of life on Earth dates from 3.8 Gya from Western Australia.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Fossil micro-organisms may have lived in hydrothermal vent precipitates from Quebec, soon after ocean formation during the Hadean, so the process appears to have been relatively rapid in terms of geological time.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Life consists of reproduction with (heritable) variations.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] That in turn implies a suite of cellular machinery including messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Those proteins included enzymes to operate its anaerobic respiration via the Wood–Ljungdahl metabolic pathway, and a DNA polymerase to replicate its genetic material.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The challenge for origin of life researchers is to explain how such a complex and tightly interlinked system could develop by evolutionary steps, as at first sight all its parts are necessary to enable it to function.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] For example, a cell, whether the LUCA or in a modern organism, copies its DNA with the DNA polymerase enzyme, which is itself produced by translating the DNA polymerase gene in the DNA.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Neither the enzyme nor the DNA can be produced without the other.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The evolutionary process could have started with molecular self-replication, self-assembly such as of cell membranes, and autocatalysis via RNA ribozymes in an RNA world environment.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The transition of non-life to life has not been observed experimentally.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Some scientists see both life and the origin of life as aspects of the same process.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The preconditions to the development of a living cell like the LUCA are known, though disputed in detail: a habitable world is formed with a supply of minerals and liquid water and sources of free energy inflows such as our Sun and geothermal heat.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic synthesis creates a range of simple organic compounds, which are assembled into polymers such as proteins and RNA.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] On the other side, the process after the LUCA is readily understood: biological evolution caused the development of a wide range of species with varied forms and biochemical capabilities.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] However, the derivation of the LUCA from simple components is far from understood.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth remains the only place where life is known, the science of astrobiology seeks evidence of life on other planets.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The advent of such polymers was most likely a critical step in prebiotic chemical evolution.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Those polymers derived, in turn, from simple organic compounds such as nucleobases, amino acids, and sugars, likely formed by reactions in the environment.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] A successful theory of the origin of life must explain how all these chemicals came into being.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] One ancient view of the origin of life, from Aristotle until the 19th century, was of spontaneous generation.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] This held that "lower" animals such as insects were generated by decaying organic substances, and that life arose by chance.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] This was questioned from the 17th century, in works like Thomas Browne's *Pseudodoxia Epidemica*.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] In 1665, Robert Hooke published the first drawings of a microorganism.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] In 1676, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek drew and described microorganisms, probably protozoa and bacteria.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Van Leeuwenhoek disagreed with spontaneous generation, and by the 1680s convinced himself, using experiments ranging from sealed and open meat incubation and the close study of insect reproduction, that the theory was incorrect.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] In 1668 Francesco Redi showed that no maggots appeared in meat when flies were prevented from laying eggs.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] By the middle of the 19th century, spontaneous generation was considered disproven.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Dating back to Anaxagoras in the 5th century BC, panspermia is the idea that life originated elsewhere in the universe and came to Earth.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The modern version of panspermia holds that life may have been distributed to Earth by meteoroids, asteroids, comets or planetoids.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] This shifts the origin of life to another heavenly body.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The advantage is that life is not required to have formed on each planet it occurs on, but in a more limited set of locations, and then spread about the galaxy to other star systems.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] There is some interest in the possibility that life originated on Mars and later transferred to Earth.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The idea that life originated from non-living matter in slow stages appeared in Herbert Spencer's 1864–1867 book *Principles of Biology*, and in William Turner Thiselton-Dyer's 1879 paper "On spontaneous generation and evolution".
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane in 1929 proposed that the earliest cells slowly self-organized from a primordial soup, the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane suggested that the Earth's prebiotic oceans consisted of a "hot dilute soup" in which organic compounds could have formed.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Bernal showed that such mechanisms could form most of the necessary molecules for life from inorganic precursors.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] In 1967, he suggested three "stages": the origin of biological monomers; the origin of biological polymers; and the evolution from molecules to cells.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] In 1952, Stanley Miller and Harold Urey carried out a chemical experiment to demonstrate how organic molecules could have formed spontaneously from inorganic precursors under prebiotic conditions like those posited by the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] It passed an electric current through a highly reducing (lacking oxygen) mixture of gases—methane, ammonia, and hydrogen, with water vapor—to form organic monomers such as amino acids.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The addition of iron and carbonate minerals, present in early oceans, produces a diverse array of amino acids.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Later work has focused on two other potential reducing environments: outer space and deep-sea hydrothermal vents.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after the Big Bang, roughly 14 Gya, the only chemical elements present in the universe were hydrogen, helium, and lithium, the three lightest atoms in the periodic table.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] These elements gradually condensed into vast clouds of gas, which collapsed under gravity into rotating protostellar disks.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Gravitational accretion of material at the hot and dense centers of these disks formed the first stars by the fusion of hydrogen.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Early stars were massive and short-lived, producing all the heavier elements by stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Such element formation proceeds to its most stable element Iron-56.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Heavier elements were formed during supernovas at the end of a star's lifecycle.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon, currently the fourth most abundant element in the universe, was formed mainly in white dwarf stars.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] As these stars reached the end of their lifecycles, they ejected heavier elements, including carbon and oxygen, throughout the universe.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] These allowed for the formation of rocky planets.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] According to the nebular hypothesis, the Solar System began to form 4.6 Gya with the gravitational collapse of part of a giant molecular cloud.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Most of the collapsing mass collected in the center, forming the Sun, while the rest flattened into a protoplanetary disk out of which the planets formed.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The age of the Earth is 4.54 Gya as found by radiometric dating of calcium-aluminium-rich inclusions in carbonaceous chrondrite meteorites, the oldest material in the Solar System.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Earth, during the Hadean eon (from its formation until 4.031 Gya,) was at first inhospitable to life.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] During its formation, the Earth lost much of its initial mass, and so lacked the gravity to hold molecular hydrogen and the bulk of the original inert gases.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after initial accretion of Earth at 4.48 Gya, its collision with Theia, a hypothesised impactor, is thought to have created the ejected debris that eventually formed the Moon.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] This impact removed the Earth's primary atmosphere, leaving behind clouds of viscous silicates and carbon dioxide.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] This unstable atmosphere was short-lived, soon condensing to form the bulk silicate Earth, leaving behind an atmosphere largely consisting of water vapor, nitrogen, and carbon dioxide, with smaller amounts of carbon monoxide, hydrogen, and sulfur compounds.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The solution of carbon dioxide in water is thought to have made the seas slightly acidic, with a pH of about 5.5.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Condensation to form liquid oceans is theorised to have occurred as early as the Moon-forming impact.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] This scenario is supported by the dating of 4.404 Gya zircon crystals with high *δ*18O values from metamorphosed quartzite of Mount Narryer in Western Australia.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The Hadean atmosphere has been characterized as a "gigantic, productive outdoor chemical laboratory," similar to volcanic gases today which still support some abiotic chemistry.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Despite the likely increased volcanism from early plate tectonics, the Earth may have been a predominantly water world between 4.4 and 4.3 Gya.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] It is debated whether crust was exposed above this ocean.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Immediately after the Moon-forming impact, Earth likely had little if any continental crust, a turbulent atmosphere, and a hydrosphere subject to intense ultraviolet light from a T Tauri stage Sun.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] It was also affected by cosmic radiation, and continued asteroid and comet impacts.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The Late Heavy Bombardment hypothesis posits that a period of intense impact occurred at 4.1 to 3.8 Gya during the Hadean and early Archean eons.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Originally it was thought that the Late Heavy Bombardment was a single cataclysmic impact event occurring at 3.9 Gya; this would have had the potential to sterilize Earth by volatilizing liquid oceans and blocking sunlight needed for photosynthesis, delaying the earliest possible emergence of life.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] More recent research questioned the intensity of the Late Heavy Bombardment and its potential for sterilisation.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] If it was not one giant impact but a period of raised impact rate, it would have had much less destructive power.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The 3.9 Gya date arose from dating of Apollo mission sample returns collected mostly near the Imbrium Basin, biasing the age of recorded impacts.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Impact modelling of the lunar surface reveals that rather than a cataclysmic event at 3.9 Gya, multiple small-scale, short-lived periods of bombardment likely occurred.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Terrestrial data backs this idea by showing multiple periods of ejecta in the rock record both before and after the 3.9 Gya marker, suggesting that the early Earth was subject to continuous impacts with less impact on extinction.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from late impacts and the then high levels of ultraviolet radiation from the sun.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The available energy is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Based on evidence from the geologic record, life most likely emerged on Earth between 4.32 and 3.48 Gya.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] In 2017, the earliest physical evidence of life was reported to consist of microbialites in the Nuvvuagittuq Greenstone Belt of Northern Quebec, in banded iron formation rocks at least 3.77 and possibly as old as 4.32 Gya.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The micro-organisms could have lived within hydrothermal vent precipitates, soon after the 4.4 Gya formation of oceans during the Hadean.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The microbes resemble modern hydrothermal vent bacteria, supporting the view that abiogenesis began in such an environment.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Later research disputed this interpretation of the data, stating that the observations may be better explained by abiotic processes in silica-rich waters, "chemical gardens," circulating hydrothermal fluids, or volcanic ejecta.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Biogenic graphite has been found in 3.7 Gya metasedimentary rocks from southwestern Greenland and in microbial mat fossils from 3.49 Gya cherts in the Pilbara region of Western Australia.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Evidence of early life in rocks from Akilia Island, near the Isua supracrustal belt in southwestern Greenland, dating to 3.7 Gya, have shown biogenic carbon isotopes.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] In other parts of the Isua supracrustal belt, graphite inclusions trapped within garnet crystals are connected to the other elements of life: oxygen, nitrogen, and possibly phosphorus in the form of phosphate, providing further evidence for life 3.7 Gya.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] In the Pilbara region of Western Australia, compelling evidence of early life was found in pyrite-bearing sandstone in a fossilized beach, with rounded tubular cells that oxidized sulfur by photosynthesis in the absence of oxygen.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon isotope ratios on graphite inclusions from the Jack Hills zircons suggest that life could have existed on Earth from 4.1 Gya.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 study inferred LUCA's age as around 4.2 Gya (4.09–4.33 Gya) by analysing pre-LUCA gene duplicates, with calibration from fossil micro-organisms, much sooner after the origin of life than previously thought.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The Pilbara region of Western Australia contains the Dresser Formation with rocks 3.48 Gya, including layered structures called stromatolites.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Their modern counterparts are created by photosynthetic micro-organisms including cyanobacteria.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] These lie within undeformed hydrothermal-sedimentary strata; their texture indicates a biogenic origin.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Parts of the Dresser formation preserve hot springs on land, but other regions seem to have been shallow seas.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] A molecular clock analysis suggests the LUCA emerged prior to 3.9 Gya.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] All chemical elements derive from stellar nucleosynthesis except for hydrogen and some helium and lithium.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Basic chemical ingredients of life – the carbon-hydrogen molecule (CH), the carbon-hydrogen positive ion (CH+) and the carbon ion (C+) – can be produced by ultraviolet light from stars.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Complex molecules, including organic molecules, form naturally both in space and on planets.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] An organic compound is a chemical whose molecules contain carbon.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets of the Solar System.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds are relatively common in space, formed by "factories of complex molecular synthesis" which occur in molecular clouds and circumstellar envelopes, and chemically evolve after reactions are initiated mostly by ionizing radiation.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Purine and pyrimidine nucleobases including guanine, adenine, cytosine, uracil, and thymine, as well as sugars, have been found in meteorites.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] These could have provided the materials for DNA and RNA to form on the early Earth.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The amino acid glycine was found in material ejected from comet Wild 2; it had earlier been detected in meteorites.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Comets are encrusted with dark material, thought to be a tar-like organic substance formed from simple carbon compounds under ionizing radiation.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] A rain of material from comets could have brought such complex organic molecules to Earth.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] During the Late Heavy Bombardment, meteorites may have delivered up to five million tons of organic prebiotic elements to Earth per year.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Currently 40,000 tons of cosmic dust falls to Earth each year.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH) are the most common and abundant polyatomic molecules in the observable universe, and are a major store of carbon.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] They seem to have formed shortly after the Big Bang, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] They are a likely constituent of Earth's primordial sea.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs have been detected in nebulae, and in the interstellar medium, in comets, and in meteorites.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] A star, HH 46-IR, resembling the sun early in its life, is surrounded by a disk of material which contains molecules including cyanide compounds, hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs in the interstellar medium can be transformed through hydrogenation, oxygenation, and hydroxylation to more complex organic compounds used in living cells.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds introduced on Earth by interstellar dust particles can help to form complex molecules, thanks to their peculiar surface-catalytic activities.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA component uracil and related molecules, including xanthine, in the Murchison meteorite were likely formed extraterrestrially, as suggested by studies of 12C/13C isotopic ratios.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] NASA studies of meteorites suggest that all four DNA nucleobases (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) have been formed in outer space.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The cosmic dust permeating the universe contains complex organics ("amorphous organic solids with a mixed aromatic–aliphatic structure") that could be created rapidly by stars.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Glycolaldehyde, a sugar molecule and RNA precursor, has been detected in regions of space including around protostars and on meteorites.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] As early as the 1860s, experiments demonstrated that biologically relevant molecules can be produced from interaction of simple carbon sources with abundant inorganic catalysts.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The spontaneous formation of complex polymers from abiotically generated monomers under the conditions posited by the "soup" theory is not straightforward.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Besides the necessary basic organic monomers, compounds that would have prohibited the formation of polymers were also formed in high concentration during the Miller–Urey experiment and Joan Oró experiments.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Biology uses essentially 20 amino acids for its coded protein enzymes, representing a very small subset of the structurally possible products.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Since life tends to use whatever is available, an explanation is needed for why the set used is so small.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide is attractive as a medium that potentially provided a source of amino acid derivatives from simple aldehyde and nitrile feedstocks.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Alexander Butlerov showed in 1861 that the formose reaction created sugars including tetroses, pentoses, and hexoses when formaldehyde is heated under basic conditions with divalent metal ions like calcium.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Breslow proposed that the reaction was autocatalytic in 1959.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Nucleobases, such as guanine and adenine, can be synthesized from simple carbon and nitrogen sources, such as hydrogen cyanide (HCN) and ammonia.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] On early Earth, HCN was likely supplied via photochemical production in a transient, highly reducing atmosphere after major impacts.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide, from the reaction of water and HCN, produces all four ribonucleotides when warmed with terrestrial minerals.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] HCN can contribute to chemical processes such as the synthesis of the amino acid glycine.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] DNA and RNA components including uracil, cytosine and thymine can be synthesized under outer space conditions, using starting chemicals such as pyrimidine from meteorites.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Pyrimidine may have formed in red giant stars, interstellar dust, or gas clouds, or on Earth via precursors such as cyanoacetylene following asteroid impacts.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] All four RNA-bases may be synthesized from formamide in high-energy density events like extraterrestrial impacts.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Several ribonucleotides for RNA formation have been synthesized in a laboratory environment which replicates prebiotic conditions via autocatalytic formose reaction.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Other pathways for synthesizing bases from inorganic materials have been reported.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Freezing temperatures assist the synthesis of purines, by concentrating key precursors such as HCN.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] However, while adenine and guanine require freezing conditions, cytosine and uracil may require boiling temperatures.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Seven amino acids and eleven types of nucleobases formed in ice when ammonia and cyanide were left in a freezer for 25 years.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] S-triazines (alternative nucleobases), pyrimidines including cytosine and uracil, and adenine can be synthesized by subjecting a urea solution to freeze-thaw cycles under a reductive atmosphere with spark discharges.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] These low-temperature reactions proceed rapidly due to eutectic freezing, which crowds impurities in microscopic pockets of liquid within the ice.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic peptide synthesis could have occurred by several routes.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Some center on high temperature/concentration conditions in which condensation becomes energetically favorable, while others use plausible prebiotic condensing agents.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Experimental evidence for the formation of peptides in uniquely concentrated environments is bolstered by work suggesting that wet-dry cycles and the presence of specific salts can greatly increase spontaneous condensation of glycine into poly-glycine chains.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Other work suggests that while mineral surfaces, such as those of pyrite, calcite, and rutile catalyze peptide condensation, they also catalyze their hydrolysis.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The authors suggest that additional chemical activation or coupling would be necessary to produce peptides at sufficient concentrations.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Thus, mineral surface catalysis, while important, is not sufficient alone for peptide synthesis.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Many prebiotically plausible condensing/activating agents have been identified, including the following: cyanamide, dicyanamide, dicyandiamide, diaminomaleonitrile, urea, trimetaphosphate, NaCl, CuCl2, (Ni,Fe)S, CO, carbonyl sulfide (COS), carbon disulfide (CS2), SO2, and diammonium phosphate (DAP).
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 experiment used a sapphire substrate with a web of thin cracks under a heat flow, mimicking deep-ocean vents, to concentrate prebiotically-relevant building blocks from a dilute mixture by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] This could help to create biopolymers such as peptides.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] A similar role has been suggested for clays, though this speculation has not been supported through experimental evidence.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The prebiotic synthesis of peptides from simpler molecules such as CO, NH3 and C, skipping the step of amino acid formation, is also very efficient.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The largest unanswered question in evolution is how simple protocells first arose and differed in reproductive contribution to the following generation, thus initiating evolution.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The lipid world theory postulates that the first self-replicating object was lipid-like.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Phospholipids form lipid bilayers (as in cell membranes) in water while under agitation.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] These molecules were not present on early Earth, but other membrane-forming amphiphilic long-chain molecules were.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] These bodies may expand by insertion of additional lipids, and may spontaneously split into two offspring of similar size and composition.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Lipid bodies may have provided sheltering envelopes for information storage, allowing the evolution of information-storing polymers like RNA.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Only one or two types of vesicle-forming amphiphiles have been studied.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Such site/compound pairs are transmissible to the daughter vesicles, leading to the emergence of distinct lineages of vesicles, subject to natural selection.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] A protocell is a self-organized, self-ordered, spherical collection of lipids proposed as a stepping-stone to life, that is capable of evolving.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembled vesicles are essential components of primitive cells.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The theory of classical irreversible thermodynamics treats self-assembly under a generalized chemical potential within the framework of dissipative systems.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that overall entropy increases, yet life is distinguished by its great degree of organization.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Therefore, a boundary is needed to separate ordered life processes from chaotic non-living matter.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] A functional protocell, which must exhibit Darwinian evolution, has not yet been achieved in a laboratory setting.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Szostak suggest that elementary protocells can give rise to primitive forms of differential reproduction, competition, and energy storage.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Competition for membrane molecules would favor stabilized membranes, suggesting a selective advantage for cross-linked fatty acids and even modern phospholipids.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Such micro-encapsulation would allow for metabolism within the membrane and the exchange of small molecules, while retaining large biomolecules inside.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Such a membrane is needed for a cell to create its own electrochemical gradient.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Vesicles can undergo an evolutionary process under pressure cycling conditions.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Simulating the systemic environment in tectonic fault zones within the Earth's crust, pressure cycling forms vesicles periodically, as well as random peptide chains which are selected for ability to integrate into the vesicle membrane.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Further selection of vesicles for stability could lead to functional peptide structures, increasing vesicle survival rate.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Life requires a loss of entropy, or disorder, as molecules organize themselves into living matter.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] At the same time, the emergence of life is associated with the formation of structures beyond a certain threshold of complexity.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Multiple sources of energy were available for chemical reactions on the early Earth.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Heat from geothermal processes is a standard energy source for chemistry.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Other examples include sunlight, lightning, atmospheric entries of micro-meteorites, and implosion of bubbles in sea and ocean waves.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] This has been confirmed by experiments and simulations.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Unfavorable reactions can be driven by highly favorable ones, as in the case of iron-sulfur chemistry.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] For example, this was probably important for carbon fixation.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon fixation by reaction of CO2 with H2S via iron-sulfur chemistry is favorable, and occurs at neutral pH and 100 °C.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Iron-sulfur surfaces, which are abundant near hydrothermal vents, can drive the production of small amounts of amino acids and other biomolecules.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] In 1961, Peter Mitchell proposed chemiosmosis as a cell's primary system of energy conversion.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism, now ubiquitous in living cells, powers energy conversion in micro-organisms and in the mitochondria of eukaryotes, making it a likely candidate for early life.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Mitochondria produce adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the energy currency of the cell used to drive cellular processes such as chemical syntheses.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism of ATP synthesis involves a closed membrane in which the ATP synthase enzyme is embedded.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The energy required to release strongly bound ATP has its origin in protons that move across the membrane.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] In modern cells, those proton movements are caused by the pumping of ions across the membrane, maintaining an electrochemical gradient.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] However, as yet, the hypothesis is untested.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA world hypothesis describes an early Earth with self-replicating and catalytic RNA but no DNA or proteins.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] It was proposed in 1962 by Alexander Rich; the term was coined by Walter Gilbert in 1986.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Many researchers concur that an RNA world must have preceded modern DNA-based life.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] However, it may not have been the first to exist.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] There may have been over 30 chemical events between pre-RNA world to near-LUCA, just involving RNA.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] RNA is central to the translation process.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Small RNAs can catalyze all the chemical groups and information transfers required for life.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] RNA both expresses and maintains genetic information in modern organisms; its components are easily synthesized under early Earth conditions.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The structure of the ribosome has been called the "smoking gun", with a central core of RNA and no amino acid side chains within 18 Å of the active site that catalyzes peptide bond formation.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] RNA replicase can both code and catalyse further RNA replication, i.e. it is autocatalytic.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Some catalytic RNAs can link smaller RNA sequences together, enabling self-replication.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Natural selection would then favor the proliferation of such autocatalytic sets.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembly of RNA may occur spontaneously in hydrothermal vents.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] A preliminary form of tRNA could have assembled into a replicator molecule.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] When this began to replicate, it may have had all three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation, and differential reproduction.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Its fitness would have depended on its ability to adapt, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and resource availability.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Starting with the work of Carl Woese from 1977, genomics studies have placed the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all modern life-forms between Bacteria and a clade formed by Archaea and Eukaryota in the phylogenetic tree of life.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] A minority of studies have placed the LUCA in Bacteria, proposing that Archaea and Eukaryota are evolutionarily derived from within Eubacteria; Thomas Cavalier-Smith suggested in 2006 that the phenotypically diverse bacterial phylum Chloroflexota contained the LUCA.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] In 2016, a set of 355 genes likely present in the LUCA was identified.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] A total of 6.1 million prokaryotic genes from Bacteria and Archaea were sequenced, identifying 355 protein clusters from among 286,514 protein clusters that were probably common to the LUCA.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The results suggest that the LUCA was anaerobic with a Wood–Ljungdahl (reductive Acetyl-CoA) pathway, nitrogen- and carbon-fixing, thermophilic.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Its cofactors suggest dependence upon an environment rich in hydrogen, carbon dioxide, iron, and transition metals.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Its genetic material was probably DNA, requiring the 4-nucleotide genetic code, messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins such as enzymes.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] LUCA likely inhabited an anaerobic hydrothermal vent setting in a geochemically active environment.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] It was evidently already a complex organism, and must have had precursors; it was not the first living thing.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] The physiology of LUCA has been in dispute.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Previous research identified 60 proteins common to all life.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p01] Metabolic reactions inferred in LUCA are the incomplete reverse Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, the pentose phosphate pathway, glycolysis, reductive amination, and transamination.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] A variety of geologic and environmental settings have been proposed for an origin of life.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] These theories are often in competition with one another as there are many views of prebiotic compound availability, geophysical setting, and early life characteristics.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] The first organism on Earth likely differed from LUCA.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Between the first appearance of life and where all modern phylogenies began branching, an unknown amount of time passed, with unknown gene transfers, extinctions, and adaptation to environmental niches.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Modern phylogenies provide more genetic evidence about LUCA than about its precursors.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Early micro-fossils may have come from a hot world of gases such as methane, ammonia, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen sulfide, toxic to much current life.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Analysis of the tree of life places thermophilic and hyperthermophilic bacteria and archaea closest to the root, suggesting that life may have evolved in a hot environment.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] The deep sea or alkaline hydrothermal vent theory posits that life began at submarine hydrothermal vents.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] William Martin and Michael Russell have suggested that this could have been in metal-sulphide-walled compartments acting as precursors for cell walls.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] These form where hydrogen-rich fluids emerge from below the sea floor, as a result of serpentinization of ultra-mafic olivine with seawater and a pH interface with carbon dioxide-rich ocean water.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] The vents form a sustained chemical energy source derived from redox reactions, in which electron donors (molecular hydrogen) react with electron acceptors (carbon dioxide); see iron–sulfur world theory.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Russell demonstrated that alkaline vents create an abiogenic proton motive force chemiosmotic gradient, ideal for abiogenesis.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Their microscopic compartments "provide a natural means of concentrating organic molecules," composed of iron-sulfur minerals such as mackinawite, endowed these mineral cells with the catalytic properties envisaged by Günter Wächtershäuser.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Electrostatic force caused by electrical potential gradient—cations like protons H+ diffuse down the electrical potential, anions in the opposite direction.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] These two gradients together can be expressed as an electrochemical gradient, providing energy for abiogenic synthesis.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] The proton motive force measures the potential energy stored as proton and voltage gradients across a membrane (differences in proton concentration and electrical potential).
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] In 2016, Martin suggested that the LUCA "may have depended heavily on the geothermal energy of the vent to survive".
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] That same year, RNA was produced in synthetic alkaline hydrothermal chimneys simulating deep-sea vents.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Researchers were able to generate RNA oligomers of up to 4 units in length.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] This RNA was synthesized using activated ribonucleotides.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Additionally, these RNA oligomers could only be synthesized under certain conditions.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Pores at deep sea hydrothermal vents are suggested to have been occupied by membrane-bound compartments which promoted biochemical reactions.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Metabolic intermediates in the Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, amino acid bio-synthetic pathways, glycolysis, the pentose phosphate pathway, and including sugars like ribose, and lipid precursors can occur non-enzymatically at conditions relevant to deep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] If the deep marine hydrothermal setting was the site, then life could have arisen as early as 4.0–4.2 Gya.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from impacts and the then high levels of solar ultraviolet radiation.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] The available energy in hydrothermal vents is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Hyperthermophily could have been a result of convergent evolution in bacteria and archaea; a mesophilic environment has been called more likely.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Production of prebiotic organic compounds at hydrothermal vents is estimated to be 108 kg/yr.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Key prebiotic compounds, such as methane are in far lower concentrations at vents than in a Miller-Urey Experiment environment.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Some organic compounds are now understood to have been formed by other geological processes and inherited by vents.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Methane, for example, more likely comes from leached fluid inclusions formed deeper in oceanic crust from magmatic carbon.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Vents do not concentrate prebiotic materials, due to strong dilution by seawater.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] This open system cycles compounds through vent minerals, leaving little residence time to accumulate.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] All modern cells rely on phosphates for nucleotide backbone and potassium for protein formation, making it likely that the first life forms shared these functions.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] These elements were not available in high quantities in the Archaean oceans.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] However, phosphate can be concentrated in lakes, as in the modern Last Chance Lake.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Submarine hydrothermal vents are not conducive to condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] An older argument was that key polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation, which supposedly would not happen in saltwater.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] However, while salinity inhibits vesicle formation from low-diversity mixtures of fatty acids, vesicle formation from a broader, more realistic mix of fatty-acid and 1-alkanol species is more resilient.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] No studies have been able to experimentally demonstrate synthesis of sugars, amino acids, nucleases, nucleosides, nucleotides, or membrane-forming fatty acids under plausible vent conditions.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Surface bodies of water provide environments that dry out and rewet.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Wet-dry cycles concentrate prebiotic compounds and enable condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, lakes and ponds receive detrital input from weathering of continental apatite-containing rocks, the most common source of phosphates.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] The amount of exposed continental crust in the Hadean is unknown, but models of early ocean depths and rates of ocean island and continental crust growth make it plausible that there was exposed land.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Another line of evidence for a surface start to life is the requirement for Ultraviolet radiation (UV) for organism function.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] UV is necessary for the formation of the U+C nucleotide base pair by partial hydrolysis and nucleobase loss.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Simultaneously, UV can be harmful and sterilising to life, especially for simple early lifeforms with little ability to repair radiation damage.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Radiation levels from a young Sun were likely greater, and, with no ozone layer, harmful shortwave UV rays would reach the surface of Earth.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] For life to begin, a shielded environment with influx from UV-exposed sources is necessary to both benefit and protect from UV.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Shielding under ice, liquid water, mineral surfaces (e.g. clay) or regolith is possible in a range of surface water settings.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Most branching phylogenies are thermophilic or hyperthermophilic, making it possible that LUCA and preceding lifeforms were similarly thermophilic.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs are formed from the heating of groundwater by geothermal activity.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] This intersection allows for influxes of material from deep penetrating waters and from surface runoff that transports eroded continental sediments.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Interconnected groundwater systems create a mechanism for distribution of life to wider area.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Mulkidjanian and co-authors argue that marine environments did not provide the ionic balance and composition universally found in cells, or the ions required by essential proteins and ribozymes, especially with respect to high K+/Na+ ratio, Mn2+, Zn2+ and phosphate concentrations.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] They argue that the only environments that do this are hot springs similar to ones at Kamchatka.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] The hypothesized pre-biotic environments are similar to hydrothermal vents, with additional components that help explain peculiarities of the LUCA.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] A phylogenomic and geochemical analysis of proteins plausibly traced to the LUCA shows that the ionic composition of its intracellular fluid is identical to that of hot springs.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] The LUCA likely was dependent upon synthesized organic matter for its growth.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments show that RNA-like polymers can be synthesized in wet-dry cycling and UV light exposure.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] These polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Potential sources of organics at hot springs might have been transported by interplanetary dust particles, extraterrestrial projectiles, or atmospheric or geochemical synthesis.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs could have been abundant in volcanic landmasses during the Hadean.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] A mesophilic start in surface bodies of waters hypothesis has evolved from Darwin's concept of a 'warm little pond' and the Oparin-Haldane hypothesis.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Freshwater bodies under temperate climates can accumulate prebiotic materials while providing suitable environmental conditions conducive to simple life forms.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Atmospheric reconstructions from geochemical proxies and models suggest that sufficient greenhouse gases were present to maintain surface temperatures between 0–40 °C.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] If so, the temperature was suitable for life to begin.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Evidence for mesophily from biomolecular studies includes Galtier's G+C nucleotide thermometer.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] G+C are more abundant in thermophiles due to the added stability of an additional hydrogen bond not present between A+T nucleotides. rRNA sequencing of modern lifeforms shows that LUCA's reconstructed G+C content was likely representative of moderate temperatures.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] The diversity of thermophiles today could be a product of convergent evolution and horizontal gene transfer rather than an inherited trait from LUCA.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] The reverse gyrase topoisomerase is found exclusively in thermophiles and hyperthermophiles, as it allows for coiling of DNA.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] This enzyme requires the complex molecule ATP to function.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] If an origin of life is hypothesised to involve a simple organism that had not yet evolved a membrane, let alone ATP, this would make the existence of reverse gyrase improbable.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, phylogenetic studies show that reverse gyrase originated in archaea, and transferred to bacteria by horizontal gene transfer, implying it was not present in the LUCA.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Cold-start theories presuppose large ice-covered regions.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Stellar evolution models predict that the Sun's luminosity was ≈25% weaker than it is today.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Fuelner states that although this significant decrease in solar energy would have formed an icy planet, there is strong evidence for the presence of liquid water, possibly driven by a greenhouse effect.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] This would mean an early Earth with both liquid oceans and icy poles.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Ice melts that form from ice sheets or glacier melts create freshwater pools, another niche capable of wet-dry cycles.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] While surface pools would be exposed to intense UV radiation, bodies of water within and under ice would be shielded, while remaining connected to exposed areas through ice cracks.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Impact melting would allow freshwater and meteoritic input, creating prebiotic components.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Near-seawater levels of sodium chloride destabilize fatty acid membrane self-assembly, making freshwater settings appealing for early membranous life.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Icy environments would trade the faster reaction rates that occur in warm environments for increased stability and accumulation of larger polymers.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments simulating Europa-like conditions of ≈20 °C have synthesised amino acids and adenine, showing that Miller-Urey type syntheses can occur at low temperatures.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] In an RNA world, the ribozyme would have had even more functions than in a later DNA-RNA-protein-world.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] For RNA to function, it must be able to fold, a process hindered by temperatures above 30 °C.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] While RNA folding in psychrophilic organisms is slower, so is hydrolysis, so folding is more successful.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Shorter nucleotides would not suffer from higher temperatures.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] The continental crust, with tectonic fault zones could present a stable and well-protected environment for long-term prebiotic evolution.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Inside these systems of cracks and cavities, water and carbon dioxide present the bulk solvents.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Their phase state could vary between liquid, gaseous and supercritical, depending on pressure and temperature.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] When forming two separate phases, the system provides optimal conditions for phase transfer reactions.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Concurrently, the contents of the tectonic fault zones are supplied with inorganic educts (e.g. carbon monoxide, hydrogen, ammonia, hydrogen cyanide, nitrogen, and phosphate) and simple organic molecules (e.g. amino acids, long-chain amines, fatty acids, long-chain aldehydes).
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Part of the tectonic fault zones is at a depth of around 1000 m.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] For carbon dioxide, it provides temperature and pressure conditions near the phase transition point between the supercritical and the gaseous state.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] This allows lipophilic organic molecules that dissolve well in supercritical CO2 to accumulate, leading to local precipitation.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Periodic pressure variations such as caused by geysers or tidal influences result in periodic phase transitions, keeping the local reaction environment in a constant non-equilibrium state.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] In presence of amphiphilic compounds (such as the long chain amines and fatty acids), subsequent generations of vesicles are formed that are selected for their stability.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Homochirality is the uniformity of materials composed of chiral (non-mirror-symmetric) units.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Living organisms use molecules with the same chirality: with almost no exceptions, amino acids are left-handed while nucleotides and sugars are right-handed.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Chiral molecules can be synthesized, but in the absence of a chiral source or a chiral catalyst, they are formed in a 50/50 (racemic) mixture of both forms.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Non-racemic mixtures can arise from racemic materials by asymmetric physical laws such as the electroweak interaction, or in asymmetric environments, such as those in which molecules are exposed to circularly polarized light of a given handedness.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] It has been hypothesized that the solar nebula was such an environment, exposed to circularly-polarized radiation from an external source before or during the epoch of planet formation.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] This proposal is consistent with the finding that some amino acids delivered to Earth in meteorites exhibit a chiral asymmetry of the same sign as terrestrial life.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] Once established, a chirality imbalance may influence subsequent chemical evolution.
[src:animal/abiogenesis-p02] A small bias in the population can be amplified by asymmetric autocatalysis, as in the Soai reaction, where a chiral molecule catalyzes its own production.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala were long thought to be a discrete phylum.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Recent genome analysis has shown that they are descended from, and should be considered as, highly modified rotifers.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] This unified taxon is sometimes known as Syndermata, or simply as Rotifera, with the acanthocephalans described as a subclass of a rotifer class Hemirotatoria.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] The earliest recognisable description of Acanthocephala – a worm with a proboscis armed with hooks – was made by Italian author Francesco Redi (1684).
[src:animal/acanthocephala] In 1771, Joseph Koelreuter proposed the name Acanthocephala.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Philipp Ludwig Statius Müller independently called them *Echinorhynchus* in 1776.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Karl Rudolphi in 1809 formally named them Acanthocephala.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] The oldest known member of the group is the Middle Jurassic (living approximately 165 million years ago) taxon *Juracanthocephalus daohugouensis* known from the Jiulongshan Formation (China).
[src:animal/acanthocephala] The fossil record of the group also includes eggs found in a coprolite from the Late Cretaceous Bauru Group of Brazil, around 70–80 million years old, likely from a crocodyliform.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] The group may have originated substantially earlier.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans are highly adapted to a parasitic mode of life, and have lost many organs and structures through evolutionary processes.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] This makes determining relationships with other higher taxa through morphological comparison problematic.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] A 2016 phylogenetic analysis of the gene order in the mitochondria suggests that Seisonidea and Acanthocephala are sister clades and that the Eurotatoria are the sister clade to this group, producing the cladogram below.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Several morphological characteristics distinguish acanthocephalans from other phyla of parasitic worms.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans lack a mouth or alimentary canal.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] This is a feature they share with the cestoda (tapeworms), although the two groups are not closely related.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Adult stages live in the intestines of their host and uptake nutrients which have been digested by the host, directly, through their body surface.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] The acanthocephalans lack an excretory system, although some species have been shown to possess flame cells (protonephridia).
[src:animal/acanthocephala] The most notable feature of the acanthocephala is the presence of an anterior, protrudable proboscis that is usually covered with spiny hooks (hence the common name: thorny or spiny headed worm).
[src:animal/acanthocephala] The proboscis bears rings of recurved hooks arranged in horizontal rows, and it is by means of these hooks that the animal attaches itself to the tissues of its host.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] The hooks may be of two or three shapes, usually: longer, more slender hooks are arranged along the length of the proboscis, with several rows of more sturdy, shorter nasal hooks around the base of the proboscis.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] The proboscis is used to pierce the gut wall of the final host, and hold the parasite fast while it completes its life cycle.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Like the body, the proboscis is hollow, and its cavity is separated from the body cavity by a *septum* or *proboscis sheath*.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Traversing the cavity of the proboscis are muscle-strands inserted into the tip of the proboscis at one end and into the septum at the other.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Their contraction causes the proboscis to be invaginated into its cavity.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] The whole proboscis apparatus can also be, at least partially, withdrawn into the body cavity, and this is effected by two retractor muscles which run from the posterior aspect of the septum to the body wall.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Some of the acanthocephalans (perforating acanthocephalans) can insert their proboscis in the intestine of the host and open the way to the abdominal cavity.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] The size of these animals varies greatly, ranging from a few millimetres in length to *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus*, which measures from 10 to 65 centimetres (3.9 to 25.6 in).
[src:animal/acanthocephala] A curious feature shared by both larva and adult is the large size of many of the cells, e.g. the nerve cells and cells forming the uterine bell.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Polyploidy is common, with up to 343n having been recorded in some species.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] The body surface of the acanthocephala is peculiar.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Externally, the skin has a thin tegument that covers the epidermis and consists of a syncytium with no cell walls.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] The syncytium is traversed by a series of branching tubules containing fluid and is controlled by a few wandering, amoeboid nuclei.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Inside the syncytium is an irregular layer of circular muscle fibres, and within this again some rather scattered longitudinal fibres; there is no endothelium.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] In their micro-structure the muscular fibres resemble those of nematodes.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Except for the absence of the longitudinal fibres the skin of the proboscis resembles that of the body, but the fluid-containing tubules of the proboscis are shut off from those of the body.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] The canals of the proboscis open into a circular vessel which runs round its base.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] From the circular canal two sac-like projections called the *lemnisci* run into the cavity of the body, alongside the proboscis cavity.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Each consists of a prolongation of the syncytial material of the proboscis skin, penetrated by canals and sheathed with a muscular coat.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] They seem to act as reservoirs into which the fluid which is used to keep the proboscis "erect" can withdraw when it is retracted, and from which the fluid can be driven out when it is wished to expand the proboscis.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] The central ganglion of the nervous system lies behind the proboscis sheath or septum.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] It innervates the proboscis and projects two stout trunks posteriorly which supply the body.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Each of these trunks is surrounded by muscles, and this nerve-muscle complex is called a *retinaculum*.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] In the male at least there is also a genital ganglion.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Some scattered papillae may possibly be sense-organs.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans have complex life cycles, involving a number of hosts, for both developmental and resting stages.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Complete life cycles have been worked out for only 25 species.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala are dioecious (an individual organism is either male or female).
[src:animal/acanthocephala] There is a structure called the *genital ligament* which runs from the posterior end of the proboscis sheath to the posterior end of the body.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] In the male, two testes lie on either side of this.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Each opens in a vas deferens which bears three diverticula or *vesiculae seminales*.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] The male also possesses three pairs of cement glands, found behind the testes, which pour their secretions through a duct into the vasa deferentia.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] These unite and end in a penis which opens posteriorly.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] In the female, the ovaries are found, like the testes, as rounded bodies along the ligament.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] From the ovaries, masses of ova dehisce into the body cavity, floating in its fluids for fertilization by male's sperm.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] After fertilization, each egg contains a developing embryo.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] (These embryos hatch into first stage larva.) The fertilized eggs are brought into the uterus by actions of the *uterine bell*, a funnel like opening continuous with the uterus.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] At the junction of the bell and the uterus there is a second, smaller opening situated dorsally.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] The bell "swallows" the matured eggs and passes them on into the uterus.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] (Immature embryos are passed back into the body cavity through the dorsal opening.) From the uterus, mature eggs leave the female's body via her oviduct, pass into the host's alimentary canal and are expelled from the host's body within feces.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Having been expelled by the female, the acanthocephalan egg is released along with the feces of the host.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] For development to occur, the egg, containing the acanthor, needs to be ingested by an arthropod, usually a crustacean (there is one known life cycle which uses a mollusc as a first intermediate host).
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Inside the intermediate host, the acanthor is released from the egg and develops into an acanthella.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] It then penetrates the gut wall, moves into the body cavity, encysts, and begins transformation into the infective cystacanth stage.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] This form has all the organs of the adult save the reproductive ones.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] The parasite is released when the first intermediate host is ingested.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] This can be by a suitable final host, in which case the cystacanth develops into a mature adult, or by a paratenic host, in which the parasite again forms a cyst.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] When consumed by a suitable final host, the cycstacant *excysts*, everts its proboscis and pierces the gut wall.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] It then feeds, grows and develops its sexual organs.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] The male uses the excretions of its *cement glands* to plug the vagina of the female, preventing subsequent matings from occurring.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Embryos develop inside the female, and the life cycle repeats.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Thorny-headed worms begin their life cycle inside invertebrates that reside in marine or freshwater systems.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] One example is *Polymorphus paradoxus.* *Gammarus lacustris*, a small crustacean that inhabits ponds and rivers, is one invertebrate that *P. paradoxus* may occupy; ducks are one of the definitive hosts.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] This crustacean is preyed on by ducks and hides by avoiding light and staying away from the surface.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] However, infection by *P. paradoxus* changes its behavior and appearance in a number of ways that increase its chance of being eaten.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] First, infection significantly reduces *G. lacustris'*s photophobia; as a result, it becomes attracted toward light and swims to the surface.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Second, an infected organism will even go so far as to find a rock or a plant on the surface, clamp its mouth down, and latch on, making it easy prey for the duck.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Finally, infection reduces the pigment distribution and amount in *G. lacustris,* causing the host to turn blue; unlike their normal brown colour, this makes the crustacean stand out and increases the chance the duck will see it.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Experiments have shown that altered serotonin levels are likely responsible for at least some of these changes in behaviour.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] One experiment found that serotonin induces clinging behavior in *G. lacustris* similar to that seen in infected organisms.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Another showed that infected *G. lacustris* had approximately 3 times as many serotonin-producing sites in its ventral nerve cord.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalosis, a disease caused by *Acanthacephalus* infection, is prevalent in aquaculture, occurring in Atlantic salmon, rainbow and brown trout, tilapia, and tambaqui.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Increasing occurrence in Brazilian farming of tambaqui has been reported, and in 2003 *Acanthacephalus* was first reported in cultured red snapper in Taiwan.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] The life cycle of *Polymorphus* spp. normally occurs between sea ducks (e.g. eiders and scoters) and small crabs.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Infections found in commercial-sized lobsters in Canada were probably acquired from crabs that form an important dietary item of lobsters.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Cystacanths occurring in lobsters can cause economic loss to fishermen.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] There are no known methods of prevention or control.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Although they rarely infect humans, worms in the phylum Acanthocephala cause the disease acanthocephaliasis in humans.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] The earliest known infection was found in a prehistoric man in Utah.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] This infection was dated to 1869 ± 160 BC.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] The species involved was thought to be *Moniliformis clarki* which is still common in the area.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] The first report of an isolate in historic times was by Lambl in 1859 when he isolated *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus* from a child in Prague.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Lindemann in 1865 reported that this organism was commonly isolated in Russia.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] The reason for this was discovered by Schneider in 1871 when he found that an intermediate host, the scarabaeid beetle grub, was commonly eaten raw.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] The first report of clinical symptoms was by Calandruccio who in 1888 while in Italy infected himself by ingesting larvae.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] He reported gastrointestinal disturbances and shed eggs in two weeks.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Subsequent natural infections have since been reported.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Eight species have been isolated from humans to date.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] *Moniliformis moniliformis* is the most common isolate.
[src:animal/acanthocephala] Other isolates include *Acanthocephalus bufonis* and *Corynosoma strumosum*.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] Members of this phylum are physiologically diverse, and can be found in a variety of environments including soil, decomposing wood, hot springs, oceans, caves, and metal-contaminated soils.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] The members of this phylum are particularly abundant in soil habitats representing up to 52% of the total bacterial community.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] Environmental factors such as pH and nutrients have been seen to drive Acidobacteriota dynamics.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] Many Acidobacteriota are acidophilic, including the first described member of the phylum, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] There is much that is unknown about Acidobacteria both in their form and function.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] Thus, this is a growing field of microbiology.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] Some of this uncertainty can be attributed to the difficulty with which these bacteria are grown in the laboratory.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] There has been recent success in propagation by using low concentrations of nutrients in combination with high amounts of CO2, yet, progress is still quite slow.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] These new methods have only allowed approximately 30% of subdivisions to have species documented.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] Additionally, many of the samples sequenced do not have taxonomic names as they have not yet been fully characterized.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] This area of study is a very current topic, and scientific understanding is expected to grow and change as new information comes to light.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] Other notable species are *Holophaga foetida*, *Geothrix fermentans*, *Acanthopleuribacter pedis* and *Bryobacter aggregatus*.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] Since they have only recently been discovered and the large majority have not been cultured, the ecology and metabolism of these bacteria is not well understood.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] However, these bacteria may be an important contributor to ecosystems, since they are particularly abundant within soils.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivisions 1, 4, and 6 are found to be particularly abundant in soils.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] As well as their natural soil habitat, unclassified subdivision 2 Acidobacteriota have also been identified as a contaminant of DNA extraction kit reagents, which may lead to their erroneous appearance in microbiota or metagenomic datasets.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 have been found to dominate in low pH conditions.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] Additionally, Acidobacteriota from acid mine drainage have been found to be more adapted to acidic pH conditions (pH 2–3) compared to Acidobacteriota from soils, potentially due to cell specialization and enzyme stability.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] The G+C content of Acidobacteria genomes are consistent within their subdivisions - above 60% for group V fragments and roughly 10% lower for group III fragments.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] The majority of Acidobacteriota are considered aerobes.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] There are some Acidobacteriota that are considered anaerobes within subdivision 8 and subdivision 23.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] It has been found that some strains of Acidobacteriota originating from soils have the genomic potential to respire oxygen at atmospheric and sub-atmospheric concentrations.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] Members of the *Acidobacteriota* phylum have been considered oligotrophic bacteria due to high abundances in low organic carbon environments.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] However, the variation in this phylum may indicate that they may not have the same ecological strategy.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] The first species, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*, of this phylum was discovered in 1991.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] However, Acidobacteriota were not recognized as a distinct clade until 1997, and were not recognized as a phylum until 2012.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] In an effort to further classify Acidobacteria, 16S rRNA gene regions were sequenced from many different strains.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] These sequences lead to the formation of subdivisions within the phyla.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] Today, there are 26 accepted subdivisions recognized in the Ribosomal Database Project.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] Much of this variety comes from populations of acidobacteria found in soils contaminated with uranium.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] Therefore, most of the known species in this phyla are concentrated in a few of the subdivisions, the largest being #1.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] Most of these microbes are aerobes, and they are all heterotrophic.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] Subdivision 1 contains 11 of the known genera in addition to the majority of the species that have been able to be cultivated thus far.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] Within the 22 known genera, there are 40 conclusive species.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] The genera are divided amongst subdivisions 3, 4, 8, 10, 23, and 1.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] As the Acidobateria are a developing area of microbiology, it is hypothesized that these numbers will change drastically with further study.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] Some members of subdivision 1 are able to use D-glucose, D-xylose, and lactose as carbon sources, but are unable to use fucose or sorbose.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 also contain enzymes such as galactosidases used in the breakdown of sugars.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 4 have been found to use chitin as a carbon source.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] Despite the presence of genetic information generally known to encode for carbohydrate processing machinery in various genera of Acidobacteria, several experimental studies have demonstrated the inability to break down various polysaccharides.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] Cellulose is the main component of plant cell walls and a seemingly opportune resource for carbon.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] However, only a single species across all subdivisions has been shown to process it, *Telmactobacter bradus* from subvision 1.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] Researchers believe that an additional factor in the lack of understanding of carbon degradation by acidobacteria may stem from the present limited ability to provide adequate cultivation conditions.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] To study the natural behavior of these bacteria, they must grow and live in a controlled, observable environment.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] If such a habitat cannot be provided, recorded data cannot reliably report on the activity of the microbes in question.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] Therefore, the inconsistencies between genome sequence based predictions and observed carbon processes may be explained by present study methods.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] There has been no clear evidence that Acidobacteriota are involved in nitrogen-cycle processes such as nitrification, denitrification, or nitrogen fixation.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] However, *Geothrix fermantans* was shown to be able to reduce nitrate and contained the norB gene.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] The NorB gene was also identified in *Koribacter verstailis* and *Solibacter usitatus*.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] In addition, the presence of the nirA gene has been observed in members of subdivision 1.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] Additionally, to date, all genomes have been described to directly uptake ammonium via ammonium channel transporter family genes.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] Acidobacteriota can use both inorganic and organic nitrogen as their nitrogen sources.
[src:animal/acidobacteriota] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:animal/acinetactis] The validity and classification of this genus is contested.
[src:animal/acinetactis] In 1914, Adolf Pascher cast doubt on *Acinetactis*, suggesting that it was a junior synonym of *Dimorpha mutans*.
[src:animal/acinetactis] Cavalier-Smith classified *Acinetactis* as a heliomonad in 1993.
[src:animal/acinetactis] Bass et al. suggested in 2009 that the genus was a cercozoan in the class Granofilosea.
[src:animal/animal] The animal kingdom is divided into five major clades, namely Porifera, Ctenophora, Placozoa, Cnidaria and Bilateria.
[src:animal/animal] The much smaller basal phylum Xenacoelomorpha have an uncertain position within Bilateria.
[src:animal/animal] Animals first appeared in the fossil record in the late Cryogenian period and diversified in the subsequent Ediacaran period in what is known as the Avalon explosion.
[src:animal/animal] Nearly all modern animal phyla first appeared in the fossil record as marine species during the Cambrian explosion, which began around 539 million years ago (Mya), and most classes during the Ordovician radiation 485.4 Mya.
[src:animal/animal] Common to all living animals, 6,331 groups of genes have been identified that may have arisen from a single common ancestor that lived about 650 Mya during the Cryogenian period.
[src:animal/animal] Historically, Aristotle divided animals into those with blood and those without.
[src:animal/animal] Carl Linnaeus created the first hierarchical biological classification for animals in 1758 with his *Systema Naturae*, which Jean-Baptiste Lamarck expanded into 14 phyla by 1809.
[src:animal/animal] In 1874, Ernst Haeckel divided the animal kingdom into the multicellular **Metazoa** (now synonymous with Animalia) and the Protozoa, single-celled organisms no longer considered animals.
[src:animal/animal] In modern times, the biological classification of animals relies on advanced techniques, such as molecular phylogenetics, which are effective at demonstrating the evolutionary relationships between taxa.
[src:animal/animal] Humans make use of many other animal species for food (including meat, eggs, and dairy products), for materials (such as leather, fur, and wool), as pets and as working animals for transportation, and services.
[src:animal/animal] Dogs, the first domesticated animal, have been used in hunting, in security and in warfare, as have horses, pigeons and birds of prey; while other terrestrial and aquatic animals are hunted for sports, trophies or profits.
[src:animal/animal] Non-human animals are also an important cultural element of human evolution, having appeared in cave arts and totems since the earliest times, and are frequently featured in mythology, religion, arts, literature, heraldry, politics, and sports.
[src:animal/animal] The word *animal* comes from the Latin noun *animal* of the same meaning, which is itself derived from Latin *animalis* 'having breath or soul'.
[src:animal/animal] The biological definition includes all members of the kingdom Animalia.
[src:animal/animal] In colloquial usage, the term *animal* is often used to refer only to nonhuman animals.
[src:animal/animal] The term *metazoa* is derived from Ancient Greek μετα *meta* 'after' (in biology, the prefix *meta-* stands for 'later') and ζῷᾰ *zōia* 'animals', plural of ζῷον *zōion* 'animal'.
[src:animal/animal] A **metazoan** is any member of the group *Metazoa*.
[src:animal/animal] Animals have several characteristics that they share with other living things.
[src:animal/animal] Animals are eukaryotic, multicellular, and aerobic, as are plants and fungi.
[src:animal/animal] Unlike plants and algae, which produce their own food, animals cannot produce their own food, a feature they share with fungi.
[src:animal/animal] Animals ingest organic material and digest it internally.
[src:animal/animal] Typically, there is an internal digestive chamber with either one opening (in Ctenophora, Cnidaria, and flatworms) or two openings (in most bilaterians).
[src:animal/animal] Animal development is controlled by Hox genes, which signal the times and places to develop structures such as body segments and limbs.
[src:animal/animal] During development, the animal extracellular matrix forms a relatively flexible framework upon which cells can move about and be reorganised into specialised tissues and organs, making the formation of complex structures possible, and allowing cells to be differentiated.
[src:animal/animal] The extracellular matrix may be calcified, forming structures such as shells, bones, and spicules.
[src:animal/animal] In contrast, the cells of other multicellular organisms (primarily algae, plants, and fungi) are held in place by cell walls, and so develop by progressive growth.
[src:animal/animal] Nearly all animals make use of some form of sexual reproduction.
[src:animal/animal] They produce haploid gametes by meiosis; the smaller, motile gametes are spermatozoa and the larger, non-motile gametes are ova.
[src:animal/animal] These fuse to form zygotes, which develop via mitosis into a hollow sphere, called a blastula.
[src:animal/animal] In sponges, blastula larvae swim to a new location, attach to the seabed, and develop into a new sponge.
[src:animal/animal] In most other groups, the blastula undergoes more complicated rearrangement.
[src:animal/animal] It first invaginates to form a gastrula with a digestive chamber and two separate germ layers, an external ectoderm and an internal endoderm.
[src:animal/animal] In most cases, a third germ layer, the mesoderm, also develops between them.
[src:animal/animal] These germ layers then differentiate to form tissues and organs.
[src:animal/animal] Repeated instances of mating with a close relative during sexual reproduction generally leads to inbreeding depression within a population due to the increased prevalence of harmful recessive traits.
[src:animal/animal] Animals have evolved numerous mechanisms for avoiding close inbreeding.
[src:animal/animal] Some animals are capable of asexual reproduction, which often results in a genetic clone of the parent.
[src:animal/animal] This may take place through fragmentation; budding, such as in *Hydra* and other cnidarians; or parthenogenesis, where fertile eggs are produced without mating, such as in aphids.
[src:animal/animal] Animals are categorised into ecological groups depending on their trophic levels and how they consume organic material.
[src:animal/animal] Such groupings include carnivores (further divided into subcategories such as piscivores, insectivores, ovivores, etc.), herbivores (subcategorised into folivores, graminivores, frugivores, granivores, nectarivores, algivores, etc.), omnivores, fungivores, scavengers/detritivores, and parasites.
[src:animal/animal] Interactions between animals of each biome form complex food webs within that ecosystem.
[src:animal/animal] In carnivorous or omnivorous species, predation is a consumer–resource interaction where the predator feeds on another organism, its prey, who often evolves anti-predator adaptations to avoid being fed upon.
[src:animal/animal] Selective pressures imposed on one another lead to an evolutionary arms race between predator and prey, resulting in various antagonistic/competitive coevolutions.
[src:animal/animal] Almost all multicellular predators are animals.
[src:animal/animal] Some consumers use multiple methods; for example, in parasitoid wasps, the larvae feed on the hosts' living tissues, killing them in the process, but the adults primarily consume nectar from flowers.
[src:animal/animal] Other animals may have very specific feeding behaviours, such as hawksbill sea turtles which mainly eat sponges.
[src:animal/animal] Most animals rely on biomass and bioenergy produced by plants and phytoplanktons (collectively called producers) through photosynthesis.
[src:animal/animal] Herbivores, as primary consumers, eat the plant material directly to digest and absorb the nutrients, while carnivores and other animals on higher trophic levels indirectly acquire the nutrients by eating the herbivores or other animals that have eaten the herbivores.
[src:animal/animal] Animals oxidise carbohydrates, lipids, proteins and other biomolecules in cellular respiration, which allows the animal to grow and to sustain basal metabolism and fuel other biological processes such as locomotion.
[src:animal/animal] Some benthic animals living close to hydrothermal vents and cold seeps on the dark sea floor consume organic matter produced through chemosynthesis (via oxidising inorganic compounds such as hydrogen sulfide) by archaea and bacteria.
[src:animal/animal] Animals originated in the ocean; all extant animal phyla, except for Micrognathozoa and Onychophora, feature at least some marine species.
[src:animal/animal] However, several lineages of arthropods begun to colonise land around the same time as land plants, between 510 and 471 million years ago, during the Late Cambrian or Early Ordovician periods.
[src:animal/animal] Vertebrates such as the lobe-finned fish *Tiktaalik* started to move on to land in the late Devonian, about 375 million years ago.
[src:animal/animal] Other notable animal groups that colonized land environments are Mollusca, Platyhelmintha, Annelida, Tardigrada, Onychophora, Rotifera, Nematoda.
[src:animal/animal] Animals occupy virtually all of earth's habitats and microhabitats, with faunas adapted to salt water, hydrothermal vents, fresh water, hot springs, swamps, forests, pastures, deserts, air, and the interiors of other organisms.
[src:animal/animal] Animals are however not particularly heat tolerant; very few of them can survive at constant temperatures above 50 °C (122 °F) or in the most extreme cold deserts of continental Antarctica.
[src:animal/animal] The collective global geomorphic influence of animals on the processes shaping the Earth's surface remains largely understudied, with most studies limited to individual species and well-known exemplars.
[src:animal/animal] The blue whale (*Balaenoptera musculus*) is the largest animal that has ever lived, weighing up to 190 tonnes and measuring up to 33.6 metres (110 ft) long.
[src:animal/animal] The largest extant terrestrial animal is the African bush elephant (*Loxodonta africana*), weighing up to 12.25 tonnes and measuring up to 10.67 metres (35.0 ft) long.
[src:animal/animal] The largest terrestrial animals that ever lived were titanosaur sauropod dinosaurs such as *Argentinosaurus*, which may have weighed as much as 73 tonnes, and *Supersaurus* which may have reached 39 metres.
[src:animal/animal] Several animals are microscopic; some Myxozoa (obligate parasites within the Cnidaria) never grow larger than 20 μm, and one of the smallest species (*Myxobolus shekel*) is no more than 8.5 μm when fully grown.
[src:animal/animal] The following table lists estimated numbers of described extant species for the major animal phyla, along with their principal habitats (terrestrial, fresh water, and marine), and free-living or parasitic ways of life.
[src:animal/animal] Species estimates shown here are based on numbers described scientifically; much larger estimates have been calculated based on various means of prediction, and these can vary wildly.
[src:animal/animal] For instance, around 25,000–27,000 species of nematodes have been described, while published estimates of the total number of nematode species include 10,000–20,000; 500,000; 10 million; and 100 million.
[src:animal/animal] Using patterns within the taxonomic hierarchy, the total number of animal species—including those not yet described—was calculated to be about 7.77 million in 2011.
[src:animal/animal] Evidence of animals is found as long ago as the Cryogenian period.
[src:animal/animal] 24-Isopropylcholestane (24-ipc) has been found in rocks from roughly 650 million years ago; it is only produced by sponges and pelagophyte algae.
[src:animal/animal] Its likely origin is from sponges based on molecular clock estimates for the origin of 24-ipc production in both groups.
[src:animal/animal] Analyses of pelagophyte algae consistently recover a Phanerozoic origin, while analyses of sponges recover a Neoproterozoic origin, consistent with the appearance of 24-ipc in the fossil record.
[src:animal/animal] The first body fossils of animals appear in the Ediacaran, represented by forms such as *Charnia* and *Spriggina*.
[src:animal/animal] It had long been doubted whether these fossils truly represented animals, but the discovery of the animal lipid cholesterol in fossils of *Dickinsonia* establishes their nature.
[src:animal/animal] Animals are thought to have originated under low-oxygen conditions, suggesting that they were capable of living entirely by anaerobic respiration, but as they became specialised for aerobic metabolism they became fully dependent on oxygen in their environments.
[src:animal/animal] Many animal phyla first appear in the fossil record during the Cambrian explosion, starting about 539 million years ago, in beds such as the Burgess Shale.
[src:animal/animal] Extant phyla in these rocks include molluscs, brachiopods, onychophorans, tardigrades, arthropods, echinoderms and hemichordates, along with numerous now-extinct forms such as the predatory *Anomalocaris*.
[src:animal/animal] The apparent suddenness of the event may however be an artefact of the fossil record, rather than showing that all these animals appeared simultaneously.
[src:animal/animal] That view is supported by the discovery of *Auroralumina attenboroughii*, the earliest known Ediacaran crown-group cnidarian (557–562 mya, some 20 million years before the Cambrian explosion) from Charnwood Forest, England.
[src:animal/animal] It is thought to be one of the earliest predators, catching small prey with its nematocysts as modern cnidarians do.
[src:animal/animal] Some palaeontologists have suggested that animals appeared much earlier than the Cambrian explosion, possibly as early as 1 billion years ago.
[src:animal/animal] Early fossils that might represent animals appear for example in the 665-million-year-old rocks of the Trezona Formation of South Australia.
[src:animal/animal] These fossils are interpreted as most probably being early sponges.
[src:animal/animal] Trace fossils such as tracks and burrows found in the Tonian period (from 1 gya) may indicate the presence of triploblastic worm-like animals, roughly as large (about 5 mm wide) and complex as earthworms.
[src:animal/animal] However, similar tracks are produced by the giant single-celled protist *Gromia sphaerica*, so the Tonian trace fossils may not indicate early animal evolution.
[src:animal/animal] Around the same time, the layered mats of microorganisms called stromatolites decreased in diversity, perhaps due to grazing by newly evolved animals.
[src:animal/animal] Objects such as sediment-filled tubes that resemble trace fossils of the burrows of wormlike animals have been found in 1.2 gya rocks in North America, in 1.5 gya rocks in Australia and North America, and in 1.7 gya rocks in Australia.
[src:animal/animal] Their interpretation as having an animal origin is disputed, as they might be water-escape or other structures.
[src:animal/animal] Animals are monophyletic, meaning they are derived from a common ancestor.
[src:animal/animal] Animals are the sister group to the choanoflagellates, with which they form the Choanozoa.
[src:animal/animal] Ros-Rocher and colleagues (2021) trace the origins of animals to unicellular ancestors, providing the external phylogeny shown in the cladogram.
[src:animal/animal] Uncertainty of relationships is indicated with dashed lines.
[src:animal/animal] The animal clade had certainly originated by 650 mya, and may have come into being as much as 800 mya, based on molecular clock evidence for different phyla.
[src:animal/animal] The relationships at the base of the animal tree have been debated.
[src:animal/animal] Other than Ctenophora, the Bilateria and Cnidaria are the only groups with symmetry, and other evidence shows they are closely related.
[src:animal/animal] In addition to sponges, Placozoa has no symmetry and was often considered a "missing link" between protists and multicellular animals.
[src:animal/animal] The presence of hox genes in Placozoa shows that they were once more complex.
[src:animal/animal] The Porifera (sponges) have long been assumed to be sister to the rest of the animals, but there is evidence that the Ctenophora may be in that position.
[src:animal/animal] Molecular phylogenetics has supported both the sponge-sister and ctenophore-sister hypotheses.
[src:animal/animal] Sponges are physically very distinct from other animals, and were long thought to have diverged first, representing the oldest animal phylum and forming a sister clade to all other animals.
[src:animal/animal] Despite their morphological dissimilarity with all other animals, genetic evidence suggests sponges may be more closely related to other animals than the comb jellies are.
[src:animal/animal] Sponges lack the complex organisation found in most other animal phyla; their cells are differentiated, but in most cases not organised into distinct tissues, unlike all other animals.
[src:animal/animal] Sponges are almost entirely sessile in their adult stage.
[src:animal/animal] Sponges lack a digestive, circulatory, respiratory, or excretory system.
[src:animal/animal] Instead, they rely on the flow of water through their bodies to perform these functions.
[src:animal/animal] Many have adapted a hollow structure to facilitate the flow of water through their bodies.
[src:animal/animal] They typically feed by drawing in water through pores, filtering out small particles of food.
[src:animal/animal] They absorb oxygen dissolved in water, and they release carbon dioxide and nitrogenous waste into water that flows through them.
[src:animal/animal] Sponges can reproduce sexually and asexually.
[src:animal/animal] Asexual reproduction happens through a variety of mechanisms including by fragmentation, where a piece of the sponge splits off and reestablishes somewhere else.
[src:animal/animal] For sexual reproduction, most sponges are hermaphrodites, they produce both egg and sperm cells.
[src:animal/animal] Comb jellies, members of Ctenophora, are radially symmetric and have digestive chambers with a single opening, which serves as both mouth and anus.
[src:animal/animal] Ctenophora have distinct tissues, but these are not organised into discrete organs.
[src:animal/animal] They move using large arrays of cilia, called swimming plates.
[src:animal/animal] They have are unique in having colloblasts, structures on their tentacles that help them catch prey.
[src:animal/animal] They have nerve cells, but lack a brain or central nervous system.
[src:animal/animal] Instead their nerves are arranged into a nerve net.
[src:animal/animal] Their nerves are very different from those of other animals, and evidence suggests that their nerves developed independently of the nerves of other animals.
[src:animal/animal] Like Ctenophora, Cnidaria are radially symmetric and have digestive chambers with a single opening, which serves as both mouth and anus.
[src:animal/animal] They also have distinct tissues that are not organised into discrete organs.
[src:animal/animal] Members of the group Anthozoa, such as sea anemones, coral, and sea pens only are sessile polyps.
[src:animal/animal] Most members of Medusozoa, including jellyfish and most hydrozoans, have a polyp form as well, but also have a motile medusae stage.
[src:animal/animal] The medusae stage are commonly known as jellyfish.
[src:animal/animal] Cnidaria are diploblastic, having only two main germ layers, ectoderm and endoderm.
[src:animal/animal] The tiny placozoans have no permanent digestive chamber and no symmetry; they superficially resemble amoebae.
[src:animal/animal] Their phylogeny is poorly defined, and under active research.
[src:animal/animal] The remaining animals, the great majority—comprising some 29 phyla and over a million species—form the Bilateria clade, which have a bilaterally symmetric body plan.
[src:animal/animal] The Bilateria are triploblastic, with three well-developed germ layers, and their tissues form distinct organs.
[src:animal/animal] The digestive chamber has two openings, a mouth and an anus, and in the Nephrozoa there is an internal body cavity, a coelom or pseudocoelom.
[src:animal/animal] These animals have a head end (anterior) and a tail end (posterior), a back (dorsal) surface and a belly (ventral) surface, and a left and a right side.
[src:animal/animal] A modern consensus phylogenetic tree for the Bilateria is shown below.
[src:animal/animal] Having a front end means that this part of the body encounters stimuli, such as food, favouring cephalisation, the development of a head with sense organs and a mouth.
[src:animal/animal] Many bilaterians have a combination of circular muscles that constrict the body, making it longer, and an opposing set of longitudinal muscles, that shorten the body; these enable soft-bodied animals with a hydrostatic skeleton to move by peristalsis.
[src:animal/animal] They also have a gut that extends through the basically cylindrical body from mouth to anus.
[src:animal/animal] Many bilaterian phyla have primary larvae which swim with cilia and have an apical organ containing sensory cells.
[src:animal/animal] However, over evolutionary time, descendant spaces have evolved which have lost one or more of each of these characteristics.
[src:animal/animal] For example, adult echinoderms are radially symmetric (unlike their larvae), while some parasitic worms have extremely simplified body structures.
[src:animal/animal] Genetic studies have considerably changed zoologists' understanding of the relationships within the Bilateria.
[src:animal/animal] Most appear to belong to two major lineages, the protostomes and the deuterostomes.
[src:animal/animal] It is often suggested that the basalmost bilaterians are the Xenacoelomorpha, with all other bilaterians belonging to the subclade Nephrozoa.
[src:animal/animal] However, this suggestion has been contested, with other studies finding that xenacoelomorphs are more closely related to Ambulacraria than to other bilaterians.
[src:animal/animal] Protostomes and deuterostomes differ in several ways.
[src:animal/animal] Early in development, deuterostome embryos undergo radial cleavage during cell division, while many protostomes (the Spiralia) undergo spiral cleavage.
[src:animal/animal] Animals from both groups possess a complete digestive tract, but in protostomes the first opening of the embryonic gut develops into the mouth, and the anus forms secondarily.
[src:animal/animal] In deuterostomes, the anus forms first while the mouth develops secondarily.
[src:animal/animal] Most protostomes have schizocoelous development, where cells simply fill in the interior of the gastrula to form the mesoderm.
[src:animal/animal] In deuterostomes, the mesoderm forms by enterocoelic pouching, through invagination of the endoderm.
[src:animal/animal] The main deuterostome taxa are the Ambulacraria and the Chordata.
[src:animal/animal] Ambulacraria are exclusively marine and include acorn worms, starfish, sea urchins, and sea cucumbers.
[src:animal/animal] The chordates are dominated by the vertebrates (animals with backbones), which consist of fishes, amphibians, reptiles, birds, and mammals.
[src:animal/animal] The protostomes include the Ecdysozoa, named after their shared trait of ecdysis, growth by moulting, Among the largest ecdysozoan phyla are the arthropods and the nematodes.
[src:animal/animal] The rest of the protostomes are in the Spiralia, named for their pattern of developing by spiral cleavage in the early embryo.
[src:animal/animal] Major spiralian phyla include the annelids and molluscs.
[src:animal/animal] In the classical era, Aristotle divided animals, based on his own observations, into those with blood (roughly, the vertebrates) and those without.
[src:animal/animal] In 1758, Carl Linnaeus created the first hierarchical classification in his *Systema Naturae*.
[src:animal/animal] In his original scheme, the animals were one of three kingdoms, divided into the classes of Vermes, Insecta, Pisces, Amphibia, Aves, and Mammalia.
[src:animal/animal] Since then, the last four have all been subsumed into a single phylum, the Chordata, while his Insecta (which included the crustaceans and arachnids) and Vermes have been renamed or broken up.
[src:animal/animal] The process was begun in 1793 by Jean-Baptiste de Lamarck, who called the Vermes *une espèce de chaos* ('a chaotic mess') and split the group into three new phyla: worms, echinoderms, and polyps (which contained corals and jellyfish).
[src:animal/animal] By 1809, in his *Philosophie Zoologique*, Lamarck had created nine phyla apart from vertebrates (where he still had four phyla: mammals, birds, reptiles, and fish) and molluscs, namely cirripedes, annelids, crustaceans, arachnids, insects, worms, radiates, polyps, and infusorians.
[src:animal/animal] This division into four was followed by the embryologist Karl Ernst von Baer in 1828, the zoologist Louis Agassiz in 1857, and the comparative anatomist Richard Owen in 1860.
[src:animal/animal] In 1874, Ernst Haeckel divided the animal kingdom into two subkingdoms: Metazoa (multicellular animals, with five phyla: coelenterates, echinoderms, articulates, molluscs, and vertebrates) and Protozoa (single-celled animals), including a sixth animal phylum, sponges.
[src:animal/animal] The protozoa were later moved to the former kingdom Protista, leaving only the Metazoa as a synonym of Animalia.
[src:animal/animal] The human population exploits a large number of other animal species for food, both of domesticated livestock species in animal husbandry and, mainly at sea, by hunting wild species.
[src:animal/animal] Marine fish of many species are caught commercially for food.
[src:animal/animal] A smaller number of species are farmed commercially.
[src:animal/animal] Humans and their livestock make up more than 90% of the biomass of all terrestrial vertebrates, and almost as much as all insects combined.
[src:animal/animal] Invertebrates including cephalopods, crustaceans, insects—principally bees and silkworms—and bivalve or gastropod molluscs are hunted or farmed for food, fibres.
[src:animal/animal] Chickens, cattle, sheep, pigs, and other animals are raised as livestock for meat across the world.
[src:animal/animal] Animal fibres such as wool and silk are used to make textiles, while animal sinews have been used as lashings and bindings, and leather is widely used to make shoes and other items.
[src:animal/animal] Animals have been hunted and farmed for their fur to make items such as coats and hats.
[src:animal/animal] Dyestuffs including carmine (cochineal), shellac, and kermes have been made from the bodies of insects.
[src:animal/animal] Working animals including cattle and horses have been used for work and transport from the first days of agriculture.
[src:animal/animal] Animals such as the fruit fly *Drosophila melanogaster* serve a major role in science as experimental models.
[src:animal/animal] Animals have been used to create vaccines since their discovery in the 18th century.
[src:animal/animal] Some medicines such as the cancer drug trabectedin are based on toxins or other molecules of animal origin.
[src:animal/animal] People have used hunting dogs to help chase down and retrieve animals, and birds of prey to catch birds and mammals, while tethered cormorants have been used to catch fish.
[src:animal/animal] Poison dart frogs have been used to poison the tips of blowpipe darts.
[src:animal/animal] A wide variety of animals are kept as pets, from invertebrates such as tarantulas, octopuses, and praying mantises, reptiles such as snakes and chameleons, and birds including canaries, parakeets, and parrots all finding a place.
[src:animal/animal] However, the most kept pet species are mammals, namely dogs, cats, and rabbits.
[src:animal/animal] There is a tension between the role of animals as companions to humans, and their existence as individuals with rights of their own.
[src:animal/animal] A wide variety of terrestrial and aquatic animals are hunted for sport.
[src:animal/animal] The signs of the Western and Chinese zodiacs are based on animals.
[src:animal/animal] In China and Japan, the butterfly has been seen as the personification of a person's soul, and in classical representation the butterfly is also the symbol of the soul.
[src:animal/animal] Animals have been the subjects of art from the earliest times, both historical, as in ancient Egypt, and prehistoric, as in the cave paintings at Lascaux.
[src:animal/animal] Major animal paintings include Albrecht Dürer's 1515 *The Rhinoceros*, and George Stubbs's c.
[src:animal/animal] Insects, birds and mammals play roles in literature and film, such as in giant bug movies.
[src:animal/animal] Animals including insects and mammals feature in mythology and religion.
[src:animal/animal] The scarab beetle was sacred in ancient Egypt, and the cow is sacred in Hinduism.
[src:animal/animal] Among other mammals, deer, horses, lions, bats, bears, and wolves are the subjects of myths and worship.
